07341nam a22015015i 9781400840106DE-B159720230127011820.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230127t20112012nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008401067 a10.1515/97814008401062doi  a(DE-B1597)453788  a(OCoLC)979745628  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aPR2807 7aLIT0042202bisacsh04a822.33223  aHI 33412rvk0(DE-625)rvk/50014:1 aLitvin, Margaret, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHamlet's Arab Journey :bShakespeare's Prince and Nasser's Ghost /cMargaret Litvin.  aCourse Book 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2011] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (296 p.) :b8 halftones. 3 tables.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTranslation/Transnation ;v2800tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tNote on Transliteration and Translation -- tIntroduction -- t1. Hamlet in the Daily Discourse of Arab Identity -- t2. Nasser ’ s Dramatic Imagination,1952–64 -- t3. The Global Kaleidoscope: How Egyptians Got Their Hamlet, 1901–64 -- t4. Hamletizing the Arab Muslim Hero, 1964–67 -- t5. Time Out of Joint, 1967–76 -- t6. Six Plays in Search of a Protagonist, 1976–2002 -- tEpilogue: Hamlets without Hamlet -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor the past five decades, Arab intellectuals have seen themselves in Shakespeare's Hamlet: their times "out of joint," their political hopes frustrated by a corrupt older generation. Hamlet's Arab Journey traces the uses of Hamlet in Arabic theatre and political rhetoric, and asks how Shakespeare's play developed into a musical with a happy ending in 1901 and grew to become the most obsessively "ed literary work in Arab politics today. Explaining the Arab Hamlet tradition, Margaret Litvin also illuminates the "to be or not to be" politics that have turned Shakespeare's tragedy into the essential Arab political text, cited by Arab liberals, nationalists, and Islamists alike. On the Arab stage, Hamlet has been an operetta hero, a firebrand revolutionary, and a muzzled dissident. Analyzing productions from Egypt, Syria, Iraq, Jordan, and Kuwait, Litvin follows the distinct phases of Hamlet's naturalization as an Arab. Her fine-grained theatre history uses personal interviews as well as scripts and videos, reviews, and detailed comparisons with French and Russian Hamlets. The result shows Arab theatre in a new light. Litvin identifies the French source of the earliest Arabic Hamlet, shows the outsize influence of Soviet and East European Shakespeare, and explores the deep cultural link between Egypt's Gamal Abdel Nasser and the ghost of Hamlet's father. Documenting how global sources and models helped nurture a distinct Arab Hamlet tradition, Hamlet's Arab Journey represents a new approach to the study of international Shakespeare appropriation.Some images inside the book are unavailable due to digital copyright restrictions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aArabic dramavEgyptxHistory and criticism. 0aArabic dramax20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aArabic dramay20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aArabic dramazEgyptxHistory and criticism. 0aCivilizationvEnglish influences. 0aDRAMAvShakespeare. 0aHamlet (Legendary character). 0aHeroes in literature. 0aLITERARY CRITICISMvShakespeare. 0aLITERARY CRITICISMzEuropeanvEnglish, Irish, Scottish, Welsh. 0aPolitics in literature. 0aShakespeare, William, 1564-1616vAppreciationvArab countries. 0aShakespeare, William, 1564-1616vTranslations into ArabicxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Middle Eastern.2bisacsh  a1970s.  aAlfred Farag